The Wealth Circulation Container
A 180-Day Guide for Moving From Mutual Aid to Community Wealth
Wealth circulates before it accumulates.

Purpose of the Wealth Circulation Container
The first container asked:
Can we gather, decide, contribute, record, care, report, and return?
The next container asked:
Can we grow without losing trust?
The institution container asked:
Can this society outlive the original people who started it?
The ecosystem container asked:
Can this society connect people, money, businesses, property, youth, elders, culture, institutions, and preparedness into a living system?
The Wealth Circulation Container asks:
Can money, skill, labor, attention, and opportunity move through the community long enough to build power?
This container moves the society from emergency support toward economic coordination.
It does not abandon mutual aid.
It builds from it.
Mutual aid teaches trust.
Trust makes contribution possible.
Contribution makes records necessary.
Records make accountability possible.
Accountability makes larger commitments safer.
Larger commitments make circulation possible.
Circulation makes community wealth possible.
Wealth does not begin with a millionaire.
Wealth begins when value stops disappearing immediately.

Core Principle
Wealth circulates before it accumulates.
A dollar can enter a community and leave after one transaction.
Or it can move through a route.
It can pay a member.
That member buys from a local business.
That business hires local help.
That worker pays dues into the society.
The society supports a youth project.
That youth learns bookkeeping.
That skill strengthens a business.
That business becomes an anchor.
That anchor supports property.
That property holds value.
That value gives the community options.
That is circulation.
Circulation is not just spending.
Circulation is organized movement with memory.
This container teaches the society how to design routes where value can move, be recorded, be protected, and return.

The Wealth Circulation Sequence
The Wealth Circulation Container follows this sequence:
Track → Pool → Route → Buy → Produce → Reinvest → Reserve → Report
Track
See where money currently goes.
Pool
Gather small, regular contributions.
Route
Choose intentional paths for money, skills, and opportunity.
Buy
Use collective demand to support aligned businesses and producers.
Produce
Help members create goods, services, skills, and solutions.
Reinvest
Return value back into the society’s goals.
Reserve
Build patient money.
Report
Show what circulated, what stayed, and what grew.

PART ONE: TRACK THE FLOW

Chapter 1: Where Does the Money Go?
Core Question
Where does money leave us every month?
Understand
Before a society can build wealth, it must know where money is already moving.
Most communities do not start with no money.
They start with money that has no memory.
Money comes in through wages, benefits, side work, business income, gifts, refunds, contracts, remittances, and public support.
Then it leaves through rent, food, transportation, utilities, debt, childcare, fees, repairs, subscriptions, insurance, taxes, emergencies, and outside businesses.
The society does not need to shame spending.
It needs to understand routes.
Where does money go?
What repeats?
What could be planned?
What could be purchased together?
What could be supplied locally?
What could be reduced?
What could be turned into community power?
A money map is not judgment.
It is vision.
Discuss
What do members spend money on every month?
Which expenses surprise us?
Which expenses repeat across households?
Where do emergencies come from poor planning versus unavoidable crisis?
Where does money leave immediately?
Where could collective action reduce cost or increase local circulation?
