Chapter 3: Build Patient Money
Core Question
Can we keep some money from moving too fast?
Understand
Not every dollar should move immediately.
Some money must be patient.
Patient money gives a society options.
It allows the society to respond without panic.
It allows the society to plan before crisis.
It allows the society to support opportunity, not only emergency.
Patient money may become:
Emergency reserve
 Operating reserve
 Opportunity fund
 Youth fund
 Business support fund
 Property stewardship fund
 Preparedness fund
 Education fund
 Legal/accounting support fund
 Equipment fund
 Travel fund
 Care fund
A reserve is not hoarding.
A reserve is care with time inside it.
But reserves require trust.
Members need to know:
Why are we holding this money?
How much are we trying to hold?
When can it be used?
Who approves use?
How is it reported?
What happens if pressure comes to spend it early?
Patient money must have rules.
Discuss
What money should be used quickly?
What money should be held?
What emergencies keep catching us unprepared?
What opportunity do we want to prepare for?
What reserve amount would create breathing room?
What rule protects the reserve?
