PART TWO: ROUTE THE FLOW

Chapter 5: Create a Buying Club
Core Question
What can we purchase together better than alone?
Understand
A buying club organizes demand.
Members already buy food, supplies, services, repairs, school items, event needs, preparedness goods, and household basics.
A buying club asks:
Can we combine demand?
Can we negotiate better terms?
Can we support aligned vendors?
Can we reduce member costs?
Can we create predictable sales for local businesses?
Can we make spending more intentional?
A buying club is not only about discounts.
It is about discipline.
It teaches members to coordinate, plan, order, pay, distribute, record, and report.
Those habits later support larger economic activity.
Start small.
One product.
One vendor.
One cycle.
One report.
Discuss
What do members already buy repeatedly?
What item or service could we coordinate?
Which vendor could handle the demand?
What would make the process simple?
What could go wrong?
How will we record and report the cycle?
