Chapter 15: Build the Reserve and Opportunity Balance
Core Question
How do we balance emergency, opportunity, and long-term wealth?
Understand
A society must balance three kinds of money:
Emergency money
 Opportunity money
 Patient money
Emergency money responds to urgent need.
Opportunity money helps members move forward.
Patient money builds long-term options.
If all money goes to emergencies, the society may never build capacity.
If all money goes to long-term goals, members may feel abandoned in crisis.
If all money goes to opportunities, urgent needs may go unmet.
Balance is stewardship.
The society should decide how contributions are divided.
For example:
50% emergency aid
 20% opportunity fund
 20% reserve
 10% operations
Or:
40% emergency aid
 25% business/youth opportunity
 25% property/preparedness reserve
 10% operations
The exact formula matters less than clarity, consistency, and review.
Discuss
Are we too emergency-focused?
Are we building enough reserve?
Are we preparing for opportunity?
What balance fits our stage?
What should change as the society matures?
How often should we review the formula?
